        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We are only interested in a continuum detection, so the correlator configuration is the standard continuum mode.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We are only interested in the source flux density and light curve, not imaging properties, so any resolution or L.A.S. are acceptable for this observation.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The peak flux density and polarization fraction are rough estimates, with the former being 50% of the target's flux density at 43 GHz and the latter being the same as that at 43 GHz. As explained in the Science Justification, the target has an extremely flat radio spectrum from 1-43 GHz with polarization fraction increasing with frequency, so we believe these are reasonable values.

The integration time is set by the desire to achieve polarimetric calibration, coverage of a full rotation of the object, and a highly significant detection. The rotation period is 3.9 hr. The binary (separation ~0.1") will be unresolved regardless of the array configuration. The focus of the observations is continuum emission and we use the standard correlator setup for this. There are no timing constraints on the observation.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
